{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> στέργω</b>, <br /> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 911, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 769, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>imperfect</i> ἔστεργον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 9.117, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Ion” 817 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>future</i> στέρξω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 458, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 18.112, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>aorist</i> ἔστερξα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th-6th c.BC(?): Semonides Iambographus 7.45, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 1023, etc.\">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]: <i>perfect</i> ἔστοργα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.104 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>passive</i>, <i>aorist</i> ἐστέρχθην [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Lycophron Tragicus 1190, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Antonius” 31, etc.\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]: <i>perfect</i> ἔστεργμαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Empedocles Poeta Philosophus 22.5, “Anthologia Graeca” 6.120 (1st c.AD: Leonidas Alexandrinus Epigrammaticus)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>love, feel affection</b>, frequently of the mutual <b>love</b> of parents and children, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 1023, “OC” 1529, 2nd c.BC: Demetrius Lacon Philosophus “Herc.” 1012.46, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; παῖς στέργει τε καὶ στέργεται ὑπὸ τῶν γεννησάντων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 754b; σ. τὰ νεογνὰ βρέφη 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Oeconomicus” 7.24 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πατέρα, τοὺς γονέας, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Electra” 1102, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 25.65, compare 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Ethica Nicomachea” 1161b18 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of the <b>love</b> of the ruled people for a ruler, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 9.113, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 292 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of the <b>love</b> of a tutelary god for the people, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 911; so ἐμὲ γὰρ ἔστερξαν.. Μοῦσαι 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 229 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of a wheedling demagogue, ὦ Δῆμ᾽, εἰ μή σε.. στέργω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Eq.” 769 \">Refs</a>]; of a city and her colonies, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.38 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of the <b>love</b> of dogs for their master, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Cynegeticus” 7.12. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> less frequently of the <b>love</b> of husband and wife, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.181, 7.69, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 577, “Aj.” 212 (_anapaest meter_); ἄλλην τιν᾽ εὐνήν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Andromache” 907, compare 468 (Lyric poetry); πόσιν στέργοντ᾽ ἔχειν [prev. author] “fragment” 1062 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of brothers and sisters, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “IA” 502 \">Refs</a>]; of friends, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" LXX.Sir.27.17, etc. \">LXX</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> seldom of sexual love, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Symposium” 8.14, 21, Sosicrates Comicus 4 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of a horse and mare, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.85 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πρόβατα ἄρνα εἰ μὴ σ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-1st c.BC: Crateuas Botanicus cited in Scholia 2nd c.BC: Nicander Epicus “Theriaca” 681 \">Refs 2nd c.BC+</a>]:—<i>middle</i>, with <i>genitive</i>, δυοῖν γυναικοῖν εἷς ἀνὴρ οὐ στέργεται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Comica Adespota” 284. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> generally, <b>to be fond of, show affection for</b>, μή μ᾽ ἔπεσιν μὲν στέργε [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 87; λόγοις ἐγὼ φιλοῦσαν οὐ στέργω φίλην 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 543 \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]; στέργει γὰρ οὐδεὶς ἄγγελον κακῶν ἐπῶν[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 277, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Vespae” 1054, etc.: also of things, οὐκ οἰκός ἐστι.. εὐνοίην.. διωθέεσθαι, ἀλλὰ σ\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]. <b>accept</b> it <b>gladly</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.104; μακράν γε.. ῥῆσιν οὐ σ. πόλις 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 273, compare “Th.” 717; ὕβριν γὰρ οὐ σ. οὐδὲ δαίμονες 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 280; ἔστερξε τὴν ἁπλῶς δίκην [prev. author] “fragment” 770; τὴν ἀλήθειαν 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 485c, etc.: reversely, στέργοι με σωφροσύνα 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 635 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <b>to be content</b> or <b>satisfied, acquiesce</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare (ἀγαπάω 111), 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 11 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] (unless, <b>having desired</b>, compare below iv), [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “OC” 7; στεργέτω 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 849e; στέρξω καὶ σιωπήσομαι 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 18.112 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; στέρξον <b>oblige me, do me the favour</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 518 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.2</b></Level3> with <i>accusative</i>, ἔστεργον τὰ παρεόντα <b>were content with, acquiesced in</b> them, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 9.117 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὴν Διὸς τυραννίδα <b>bear with</b> it, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 11; ἐθέλω τάδε μὲν σ. δύστλητά περ ὄντα [prev. author] “Ag.” 1570 (_anapaest meter_), compare “Eu.” 673; ἀνάγκῃ προὔμαθον σ. κακά 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 538, compare 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Phoenissae” 1685, “PGrenf.” 1.53.21 (4th c.AD)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; σ. τὴν γυναῖκα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 486, compare 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Andromache” 180; τὴν τύχην 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 55.22. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.3</b></Level3> with <i>dative</i>, σ. τοῖσι σοῖς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Supplices” 257; τοῖς παροῦσιν 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator “Epistulae” 2.23; τῇ ἐμῇ τύχῃ 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Hp.Ma.” 295b; ταῖς ὑμετέραις γνώσεσι 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 26.5; στέρξαι καὶ ἐμμεῖναι τῇ δίκῃ “Sammelb.” 5681.32 (5th c.AD)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; also σ. ἐπὶ τούτῳ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 39.6; ἐν μικροῖς 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Electra” 407. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.4</b></Level3> with <i>participle</i>, οὐ γὰρ ἔχω πῶς ἂν στέρξαιμι κακὸν τόδε λεύσσων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 992 (_anapaest meter_); σ. ξυμφορᾷ νικώμενοι 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 458 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; Ζεὺς εἴτ᾽ Ἀΐδης ὀνομαζόμενος στέργεις whether <b>thou likest</b> to be named Zeus or Hades, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “fragment” 912 (_anapaest meter_). \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.5</b></Level3> rarely with <i>infinitive</i>, οὐκ ἔστεργέ σοι ὅμοιος εἶναι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Ion” 817. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__IV</b></Level2> <b>desire, entreat</b>, with <i>accusative</i> et <i>infinitive</i>, Ἀπόλλω καὶ κασιγνήταν.. στέργω μολεῖν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1094 (Lyric poetry); μειλιχίοις στέρξοι τε παραιφάμενος ἐπέεσσιν 5th-6th c.AD: Orphica “Argonautica” 771 (assuming variant); for 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 11 see above 111.1. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G21124","accentedUnicode":"στέργω","shortDef":"desire, entreat","mediumDef":"desire, entreat","stepGloss":"to desire","stepTransliteration":"stergō","count":0,"_step_Type":"verb"}]}